      92                 :            : // For those who are interested, varint encoding is defined as follows:
      93                 :            : //
      94                 :            : // The encoding operates on unsigned integers of up to 64 bits in length.
      95                 :            : // Each byte of the encoded value has the format:
      96                 :            : // * bits 0-6: Seven bits of the number being encoded.
      97                 :            : // * bit 7: Zero if this is the last byte in the encoding (in which
      98                 :            : //   case all remaining bits of the number are zero) or 1 if
      99                 :            : //   more bytes follow.
     100                 :            : // The first byte contains the least-significant 7 bits of the number, the
     101                 :            : // second byte (if present) contains the next-least-significant 7 bits,
     102                 :            : // and so on.  So, the binary number 1011000101011 would be encoded in two
     103                 :            : // bytes as "10101011 00101100".
     104                 :            : //
     105                 :            : // In theory, varint could be used to encode integers of any length.
     106                 :            : // However, for practicality we set a limit at 64 bits.  The maximum encoded
     107                 :            : // length of a number is thus 10 bytes.

     455                 :            :   //
     456                 :            :   // By default, when parsing extensions, the parser looks for extension
     457                 :            :   // definitions in the pool which owns the outer message's Descriptor.
     458                 :            :   // However, you may call SetExtensionRegistry() to provide an alternative
     459                 :            :   // pool instead.  This makes it possible, for example, to parse a message
     460                 :            :   // using a generated class, but represent some extensions using
     461                 :            :   // DynamicMessage.
     462                 :            : 
     463                 :            :   // Set the pool used to look up extensions.  Most users do not need to call
     464                 :            :   // this as the correct pool will be chosen automatically.
     465                 :            :   //
     466                 :            :   // WARNING:  It is very easy to misuse this.  Carefully read the requirements
     467                 :            :   //   below.  Do not use this unless you are sure you need it.  Almost no one
     468                 :            :   //   does.
     469                 :            :   //
     470                 :            :   // Let's say you are parsing a message into message object m, and you want
     471                 :            :   // to take advantage of SetExtensionRegistry().  You must follow these
     472                 :            :   // requirements:
     473                 :            :   //
     474                 :            :   // The given DescriptorPool must contain m->GetDescriptor().  It is not
     475                 :            :   // sufficient for it to simply contain a descriptor that has the same name
     476                 :            :   // and content -- it must be the *exact object*.  In other words:
     477                 :            :   //   assert(pool->FindMessageTypeByName(m->GetDescriptor()->full_name()) ==
     478                 :            :   //          m->GetDescriptor());
     479                 :            :   // There are two ways to satisfy this requirement:
     480                 :            :   // 1) Use m->GetDescriptor()->pool() as the pool.  This is generally useless
     481                 :            :   //    because this is the pool that would be used anyway if you didn't call
     482                 :            :   //    SetExtensionRegistry() at all.
     483                 :            :   // 2) Use a DescriptorPool which has m->GetDescriptor()->pool() as an
     484                 :            :   //    "underlay".  Read the documentation for DescriptorPool for more
     485                 :            :   //    information about underlays.
     486                 :            :   //
     487                 :            :   // You must also provide a MessageFactory.  This factory will be used to
     488                 :            :   // construct Message objects representing extensions.  The factory's
     489                 :            :   // GetPrototype() MUST return non-NULL for any Descriptor which can be found
     490                 :            :   // through the provided pool.
     491                 :            :   //
     492                 :            :   // If the provided factory might return instances of protocol-compiler-
     493                 :            :   // generated (i.e. compiled-in) types, or if the outer message object m is
     494                 :            :   // a generated type, then the given factory MUST have this property:  If
     495                 :            :   // GetPrototype() is given a Descriptor which resides in
     496                 :            :   // DescriptorPool::generated_pool(), the factory MUST return the same
     497                 :            :   // prototype which MessageFactory::generated_factory() would return.  That
     498                 :            :   // is, given a descriptor for a generated type, the factory must return an
     499                 :            :   // instance of the generated class (NOT DynamicMessage).  However, when
     500                 :            :   // given a descriptor for a type that is NOT in generated_pool, the factory
     501                 :            :   // is free to return any implementation.

     504                 :            :   // accessed via the standard (non-reflection) extension accessor methods,

     508                 :            :   // way the code could end up accessing it via the standard accessors -- the
     509                 :            :   // only way to access the extension is via reflection.  When using reflection,

     513                 :            :   // Using DynamicMessageFactory on which you have called
